      <text xml:lang="en">
            <body>
                  <div type="article">
                        <head><title type="main">
                                    <hi rend="bold">To EXPLORE the <rs><placeName type="island"
                                                  key="#i_sn">STRANGE ISLAND of SAN
                                                  NICOLAS</placeName></rs></hi>
                              </title>
                              <title type="sub">An Expedition from the <orgName type="institution"
                                          key="#in_ucb">University of California</orgName> Will
                                    Visit <rs><placeName type="island" key="#i_sn">the Grewsome Land
                                                that is Spread Over with Skulls and Thighbones of
                                                  <rs><orgName type="nativeamericantribes"
                                                  key="#natam_NicolenoTongva">a Lost
                                                  Race</orgName></rs></placeName></rs></title></head>
                        <div type="section">
                              <p><span type="trope" n="5">AN air of mystery pervades each of
                                                  <rs><placeName type="island" key="#i_chi">the
                                                  little islands in the scant
                                                  archipelago</placeName></rs> off the coast of
                                                <placeName type="state" key="#st_cal"
                                                >California</placeName>.</span></p>
                              <p><span type="trope" n="5"><rs><placeName type="island" key="#i_scl"
                                                  >San Clemente Island</placeName></rs> is strewn
                                          with enormous prehistoric mortars and pestles, and here
                                          and there are numerous evidences that <rs><orgName
                                                  type="nativeamericantribes"
                                                  key="#natam_GabrilenoTongva">a giant
                                                  race</orgName></rs> lived there before the
                                          Portuguese navigator, <rs><persName type="seaman"
                                                  key="#jca">Cabrillo</persName></rs>, sailed for
                                          conquest up the coast of <placeName type="region"
                                                key="#re_upcal">Alta, Cal.</placeName>, in <date
                                                when="1542">1542</date>. <placeName type="island"
                                                key="#i_scatalina">Santa Catilina</placeName> is
                                          indented by many strange caves, weird grottos, where one
                                          may see remains of <rs><orgName
                                                  type="nativeamericantribes"
                                                  key="#natam_GabrilenoTongva">a race of fishers and
                                                  artisans</orgName></rs> with shells. <placeName
                                                type="island" key="#i_sm">San Miguel
                                                Island</placeName> has been the scene of titanic
                                          erosions by ice, water, and sand. The grotesque pillars
                                          that lift themselves above <rs><placeName type="island"
                                                  key="#i_sm">the island</placeName></rs> level, the
                                          winding caves that twist from the shores into the heart of
                                          the island, and the roaring gulches and cañons all
                                          comprise a spot rich in possibilities for both scientist
                                          and dreamer. <placeName type="island" key="#i_scruz">Santa
                                                Cruz Island</placeName> is used as a pasturage for
                                          thousands of sheep, and it, too, is full of absorbing
                                          interest regarding extinct races of <rs><orgName
                                                  type="nativeamericantribes" key="#natam_chumash"
                                                  >Aborigines</orgName></rs>. The Smithsonian
                                          Institution scientists have gathered tons of stone, shell,
                                          and bone utensils and personal ornaments from <placeName
                                                type="island" key="#i_scruz">Santa
                                          Cruz</placeName>.</span>
                                    <span type="trope" n="6"><span type="trope" n="5">But <placeName
                                                  type="island" key="#i_sn">San Nicolas
                                                  Island</placeName> has by far the most abundant
                                                evidences of <rs><orgName
                                                  type="nativeamericantribes"
                                                  key="#natam_NicolenoTongva">a tribe</orgName></rs>
                                                of unusually tall and strong people who must have
                                                vanished almost in a night. Of all the California
                                                archipelagoes this is the most
                                          mysterious.</span></span></p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                              <head><title type="main">As Desolate as <rs><date when="1542">360
                                                  Years Ago</date></rs>.</title></head>
                              <p>Notwithstanding <rs><placeName type="island" key="#i_chi">the
                                                islands</placeName></rs>&#8212;known on <placeName
                                          type="region" key="#re_paccoast">the Pacific
                                          coast</placeName> as <placeName type="island" key="#i_chi"
                                          >the Channel Islands</placeName>&#8212;are but from thirty
                                    to fifty miles out in the blues of the ocean, they seldom are
                                    visited. Every few years an exploring expedition goes to them
                                    for a season of scientific study, but, with the exception of
                                          <placeName type="island" key="#i_scatalina">Santa
                                          Catalina</placeName>&#8212;a famous summer resort for
                                    California pleasure-seekers and anglers&#8212;a half-dozen
                                    visitors do not land at any of <rs><placeName type="island"
                                                key="#i_chi">the islands</placeName></rs> once a
                                    year. Today <rs><placeName type="island" key="#i_chi">the
                                                islands</placeName></rs> remain as lonely and
                                    desolate as they did long before the first white face sailed up
                                          <placeName type="region" key="#re_paccoast">the
                                          coast</placeName>&#8212;<rs><date when="1542">360 years
                                                ago</date></rs>. <span type="trope" n="5"><span
                                                type="trope" n="6"><rs><orgName type="group"
                                                  key="#natam_NicolenoTongva; #natam_GabrilenoTongva; #natam_chumash"
                                                  >The races</orgName></rs> which occupied
                                                  <rs><placeName type="island" key="#i_chi">these
                                                  islands</placeName></rs> are as much of a mystery
                                                as ever, and so far science is baffled in inquiring
                                                what sort of folk <rs><orgName type="group"
                                                  key="#natam_NicolenoTongva; #natam_GabrilenoTongva; #natam_chumash"
                                                  >these aboriginal settlers</orgName></rs> were,
                                                [ho]w they lived, what they believed, and
                                                esp[eci]ally how they so suddenly and completel[y]
                                                disappeared from the face of the
                                          earth.</span></span></p>
                              <p>The <placeName type="institution" key="#in_ucb">University of
                                          California, at Berkeley</placeName>, is about to begin the
                                    mos[t] thorough exploration ever made of <placeName
                                          type="island" key="#i_sn">San N[ic]olas
                                    Island</placeName>, which lies sixty miles off the coast of
                                                <rs><placeName type="county" key="#co_ventura"
                                                >Ventura</placeName></rs> and <rs><placeName
                                                type="island" key="#co_sb">Santa Barbara
                                                Counties.</placeName></rs></p>
                        </div>
                        <div type="section">
                              <head><title type="main">Skeletons Dot Hillsides.</title></head>
                              <p>As far back as the memory of any person in <placeName type="region"
                                          key="#re_socal">southern California</placeName> runs
                                    hundreds of white skeletons have dotted the valleys and
                                    hillsides of <placeName type="island" key="#i_sn">San
                                          Nicolas</placeName>. <span type="trope" n="5">Strange
                                          utensils of serpentine, sandstone, and steatite are found
                                          there among the human bones, and <rs><placeName
                                                  type="island" key="#i_sn">the
                                                island</placeName></rs> and <rs><orgName
                                                  type="nativeamericantribes"
                                                  key="#natam_NicolenoTongva">its
                                                  inhabitants</orgName></rs> have a history so
                                          curious that it is difficult of comprehension.</span></p>
                              <p><span type="trope" n="6">In <date when="1835">1835</date>
                                          <rs><persName type="group" key="#ndur; #aji; #misfats">the
                                                  Franciscan padres in Santa Barbara
                                                  mission</persName></rs>, learning that there were
                                          but <persName type="group" key="#bhagroup">sixteen of the
                                                strange and almost extinct Indian race</persName>
                                          then living there, determined to rescue them from
                                                  <rs><placeName type="island" key="#i_sn">the
                                                  island</placeName></rs></span>. They went over in
                                                <rs><name type="ship" key="#sh_peoresnada">a
                                                sloop</name></rs> and succeeded, as they thought, in
                                    getting all on board. At the last moment <rs><persName
                                                type="nativeamerican" key="#lw">an Indian
                                                woman</persName></rs> returned for <rs><persName
                                                type="nativeamerican" key="#lwchild">her
                                                child</persName></rs>, and one of the frequent
                                    storms of <placeName type="island" key="#i_chi">the Channel
                                          Islands</placeName> springing up, <rs><name type="ship"
                                                key="#sh_peoresnada">the sloop</name></rs> was
                                    driven away without her. <span type="trope" n="6"><rs><name
                                                  type="ship" key="#sh_peoresnada">The
                                                sloop</name></rs> went on the rocks of <placeName
                                                type="region" key="#re_PointConception">Point
                                                Conception</placeName> and <rs><persName
                                                  type="group" key="#bhagroup">all on
                                                  board</persName></rs> was [sic] lost.</span></p>
                              <p><rs><date when="1851">Sixteen years later</date></rs>
                                    <persName type="frontiersmen" key="#gni">Captain George
                                          Nidever</persName> and <rs><persName type="group"
                                                key="#tje; #natam_missionindians">two
                                          men</persName></rs> went from the coast on <rs><name
                                                type="ship" key="#sh_nidever">a sloop</name></rs> to
                                    hunt sea otter off <placeName type="island" key="#i_sn">San
                                          Nicolas</placeName>. <span type="trope" n="4">On landing,
                                          they were, like <persName type="fictional" key="#rcr"
                                                >Cruseo [Crusoe]</persName>, astonished to find
                                          human footprints in the sand. They saw no one, however,
                                          and a storm compelled them to put to sea.</span></p>
                        </div>
                        <div type="section">
                              <head><title type="main"><span type="trope" n="4">Mystery of Woman's
                                                Fate.</span></title></head>
                              <p><span type="trope" n="4">It was <rs><date when="1853">two years
                                                  thereafter</date></rs> that <rs><persName
                                                  type="frontiersmen" key="#gni">the adventurous
                                                  Captain</persName></rs>, revolving in his mind the
                                          sight of the footprints in <rs><placeName type="island"
                                                  key="#i_sn">the uncanny island</placeName></rs>,
                                          determined to go and discover and bring over <rs><persName
                                                  type="nativeamerican" key="#lw">the lonely
                                                  woman</persName></rs> of whom he hasd vaguely
                                          heard. <rs><persName type="group"
                                                  key="#cdi; #col; #cook; #msh; #poli; #nsk; #hva"
                                                  >Men</persName></rs> accompanied him, and at
                                          length they saw on the surf-beaten shore <rs><persName
                                                  type="nativeamerican" key="#lw">a
                                                woman</persName></rs> with long, tawny hair, dressed
                                          in a queer garb of colored bird skins, and scraping with a
                                          bone knife the blubber from a seal.</span></p>
                              <p><span type="trope" n="1">They surrounded and approached her
                                          stealthily, and, although suddenly, confronted, she did
                                          not appear in the least afraid, but smiled, and then,
                                          falling on her knees, prayed to the sun. <rs><persName
                                                  type="nativeamerican" key="#lw">The wild
                                                  woman</persName></rs> offered no objection when by
                                          signs she was made to understand that she was to go with
                                          them in <rs><name type="ship" key="#sh_nidever">the
                                                  boat</name></rs>.</span></p>
                              <p>They reached <placeName type="city" key="#ci_sb">Santa
                                          Barbara</placeName>, across the rough sea, and the first
                                    thing <rs><persName type="nativeamerican" key="#lw">the Indian
                                                woman</persName></rs> saw was <persName
                                          key="#riderhorseman; #mrni; #jsh; #ssh">Dr. S. L.
                                          Shaw</persName>, now 80 years old, and yet living there,
                                    riding a horse. She had never seen or heard of any object like
                                    it, and thought <rs><persName
                                                key="#riderhorseman; #mrni; #jsh; #ssh">the
                                                man</persName></rs> and horse were one, and she
                                    knelt on the shore and offered her devotions to it. <span
                                          type="trope" n="6">Two weeks afterward <rs><persName
                                                  type="nativeamerican" key="#lw">the last
                                                  inhabitant of rock-ribbed, tempest-tossed San
                                                  Nicolas</persName></rs> died from eating food to
                                          which she was unaccustomed, furnished by her rescuers, and
                                          the curtain fell on <rs><orgName
                                                  type="nativeamericantribes"
                                                  key="#natam_NicolenoTongva">her
                                                race</orgName></rs> forever.</span></p>
                        </div>
                        <div type="section">
                              <head><title type="main">Subject of Many Romances.</title></head>
                              <p>In speaking of that death at a meeting of the <orgName
                                          type="organization" key="#socalmedicalsociety">Southern
                                          California Medical society</orgName> the other day
                                                <rs><persName key="#wli">Dr. Walter
                                                Lindley</persName></rs> said that if <rs><persName
                                                type="nativeamerican" key="#lw">the
                                          woman</persName></rs> could have been spared a few years
                                    of life a story of <rs><orgName type="nativeamericantribes"
                                                key="#natam_NicolenoTongva">one of the strangest
                                                races</orgName></rs> that ever lived in
                                                <rs><placeName type="region" key="#re_sw">the
                                                Southwest</placeName></rs>, and that had no
                                    contamination with the whites, might have been learned.
                                                <rs><persName type="nativeamerican" key="#lw">The
                                                woman</persName></rs>, known as the "Lone Woman of
                                    San Nicolas," has been the subject of a score of romances and
                                    poems, and food for a lot of philosophy on the <placeName
                                          type="region" key="#re_paccoast">Pacific coast</placeName>
                                    for years.</p>
                              <p><span type="trope" n="5"><placeName type="island" key="#i_sn">San
                                                Nicolas</placeName> is ten miles long and four miles
                                          wide at the widest point. Nothing more desolate than the
                                          general appearance of <rs><placeName type="island"
                                                  key="#i_sn">the island</placeName></rs> can be
                                          imagined. As far as the eye can trace there are
                                          innumerable circular depressions, showing where primitive
                                          dwellings once stood. Not a vestige remains of the
                                          materials used in the construction of these rancherias.
                                          Hundreds of shell mounds are scattered about, and are
                                          found to consist of astonishing numbers of mollusks, the
                                          bones of every species of fish found in the channel,
                                          skeletons of seals, sea elephants, whales, sea otter, the
                                          island fox, and various aquatic birds. Without question
                                          these animals were used for food by the tribes that once
                                          thronged these boundaries. There are also numerous canine
                                          skeletons, several of which indicate a species of bull
                                          terrier. Judging from the immense quantities of dead land
                                          mollusks everywhere, there must have been a time when
                                                  <rs><placeName type="island" key="#i_sn">the
                                                  island</placeName></rs> supported luxuriant
                                          vegetation. Of all this verdure nothing is seen today but
                                          a few stunted thorn bushed and now and then a cactus
                                          forlornly reaching its grotesque arms out of interminable
                                          sweeps of sand.</span></p>
                        </div>
                        <div type="section">
                              <head><title type="main">Many Utensils; Few Weapons.</title></head>
                              <p><span type="trope" n="5">An examination of some of the mounds
                                          discloses all sorts of curious utensils, stone cooking
                                          pots, water olias, mortars, pestles, drills, bone needles,
                                          and fishhooks, shell beads, charm stones, pipes, cups, and
                                          a few arrow heads, spear points, and swords made of
                                          bone.</span> The absence of many weapons proves the
                                    peaceful attributes of <rs><orgName type="nativeamericantribes"
                                                key="#natam_NicolenoTongva">the
                                          islanders</orgName></rs>. Small imitations of boats and
                                    fish carved from crystallized talc and serpentine also show a
                                    rudimentary knowledge of the art of sculpture. In many places
                                    conical piles of small black pebbles contrast oddly with the
                                    white land. In some instances these shells were closely packed
                                    in abalone shells. No trace is seen of the "brush pens," in
                                    which <rs><persName type="nativeamerican" key="#lw">the lone
                                                woman of San Nicolas</persName></rs> for years found
                                    her only shelter from the cutting wind and sand. <span
                                          type="trope" n="6">Nature, ever unmindful of the
                                          individual, long since emerged the super-human efforts of
                                          this courageous life into the universal fate of
                                                  <rs><orgName type="nativeamericantribes"
                                                  key="#natam_NicolenoTongva">an entire
                                                  race</orgName></rs>. Indeed, every foot of
                                                  <rs><placeName type="island" key="#i_sn">this
                                                  strange island</placeName></rs> is eloquent of the
                                          extinction of <rs><orgName type="nativeamericantribes"
                                                  key="#natam_NicolenoTongva">an almost unheard-of
                                                  people</orgName></rs>.</span></p>
                              <p>At the extreme west end of <rs><placeName type="island" key="#i_sn"
                                                >the island</placeName></rs> there is a colossal
                                    precipice 1,000 feet in height, its chasmed and slitted face
                                    softened by a luxuriant growth of emerald moss and lichens. The
                                    most grewsome of all the sights on <rs><placeName type="island"
                                                key="#i_sn">this strange island</placeName></rs> is
                                    to be seen on the broad plateau on the south side of the Chinese
                                    camp, at <rs><placeName type="region" key="#re_chineseharbor"
                                                >Coral Harbor</placeName></rs>. Here acres of the
                                    naked sand are littered with hundreds of disjointed skeletons
                                    and present the most reckless illustration of the "ground plan"
                                    of humanity that imagination can picture. Measurements have been
                                    made by several scientists of the thigh, leg, and arm bones, and
                                    literally bushels of skulls and other parts of the human frame
                                    have been brought to <rs><placeName type="city" key="#ci_la">Los
                                                Angeles</placeName></rs> from <rs><placeName
                                                type="island" key="#i_sn">San
                                          Nicolas</placeName></rs> for investigation.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div type="section">
                              <head><title type="main"><rs><orgName type="nativeamericantribes"
                                                  key="#natam_NicolenoTongva">Men of Giant
                                                  Physique</orgName></rs>.</title></head>
                              <p><span type="trope" n="5">The general opinion is that the physiques
                                          of <rs><orgName type="nativeamericantribes"
                                                  key="#natam_NicolenoTongva">the Indian
                                                  race</orgName></rs> that swarmed over
                                                  <rs><placeName type="island" key="#i_sn">the
                                                  island</placeName></rs> then were much larger than
                                          those of any civilized race of today, and that some of
                                          them must have been seven feet three inches tall. The
                                          skulls of <rs><orgName type="nativeamericantribes"
                                                  key="#natam_NicolenoTongva">this extinct
                                                  tribe</orgName></rs> often measure several inches
                                          more than some of the large skulls of today.</span> Many
                                    skulls [f]ound lying about on the island show tha[t]
                                                <rs><orgName type="nativeamericantribes"
                                                key="#natam_NicolenoTongva">[their]
                                                possessors</orgName> must have suffered death from a
                                          club or blunt battle ax. No one has ever yet found a skull
                                          on <placeName type="island" key="#i_sn">San
                                                Nicolas</placeName></rs> that shows marks of a
                                    bullet. There are many collar bones and shoulder blades, broken
                                    and crushed, so that it is evident their owners were slain with
                                    some such instrument as a war club or bowlder. <span
                                          type="trope" n="11">Scientists say that the favorite
                                          weapon in warfare with <rs><orgName type="group"
                                                  key="#rfurcompany; #natam_aleuts">the Aleutian
                                                  savage tribes</orgName></rs> a century or more ago
                                          was a club or bludgeon, and this fact fits with the stray
                                          tradition that <rs><orgName type="group"
                                                  key="#rfurcompany; #natam_aleuts">the
                                                  Aleutian[s]</orgName></rs> came down and
                                          completely destroyed <rs><orgName type="group"
                                                  key="#natam_NicolenoTongva; #natam_GabrilenoTongva; #natam_chumash"
                                                  >the people of the Channel Islands</orgName></rs>
                                          about the year <date when="1570">1570</date>.</span></p>
                        </div>
                  </div>
            </body>
      </text>
